/gtr:status><gtr:grantCategory>Fellowship</gtr:grantCategory><gtr:grantReference>ES/G000077/1</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>From birth, infants show the ability to copy the actions of those around them, such as a parent sticking out their tongue. This 'neonatal imitation' has been proposed to be a possible precursor for later cultural learning. Additionally, it allows the infant to engage in social interactions with those around them, namely their parents and siblings. Older children show the ability for more precise imitative abilities, including the replication of actions involving tools.&amp;nbsp; The social interactions that facilitate observational learning are common within the daily experiences of children and it has been suggested that forms of observational learning evolved in humans to facilitate the acquisition of culture, a fundamental human adaptation. Through this one-year fellowship research conducted by the author for their PhD will be disseminated via publications and conference presentations, both in the UK and internationally. Secondly, the fellowship will allow for the planning of future research in which will encompass both an ontogenetic and comparative approach.
